BAM Files Solutions

8/27/2018

GenomicAlignments

The purpose of this exercise is to explore BAM files and the data they contain. We’ll extract the sequences and qualities of aligned reads, and draw simple plots to illustrate their properties.

The dataset is actually part of an R package, Pasilla dataset. It’s already in our workshop folder, so we can install it from there.

install.packages("/home/ace/ace_workshop/ace_bioconductor/pasillaBamSubset_0.18.0.tar.gz", repos=NULL)

We will use the Rsamtools and ShortRead libraries in addition to the pasillaBamSubset we just installed.

library(Rsamtools)
library(ShortRead)
library(pasillaBamSubset)

Exercises

  1. Use ScanBamParam to create an object that restricts the information extracted from the BAM file. Restrict the information using readGAlignments to select reads that align to the plus strand (isMinusStrand=FALSE). readGAlignments inputs alignment information; also arrange to input sequence and quality information using what=c(‘seq’, ‘qual’). You might also find this page useful: Decoding SAM Flags
flag <- scanBamFlag(isMinusStrand=FALSE)
param <- ScanBamParam(what=c("seq", "qual"), flag=flag)
  1. Input the sequences and qualities using readGAlignments, providing the file path returned by untreated1_chr4 (a ‘convenience’ function from the pasillaBamSubset package) and the ScanBamParam object created in the previous question.
fl <- untreated1_chr4()
res <- readGAlignments(fl, param=param)
  1. Use alphabetByCycle to summarize nucleotide use by cycle; plot the relationship between cycle and use. Might be a little tricky! Try examining the res object. Were you expecting this? What is going on?
library(magrittr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
abc <- alphabetByCycle(attr(res, "elementMetadata")$seq)
colnames(abc) <-1:ncol(abc)
rn <- row.names(abc)
abc <- cbind.data.frame(nt=rn, abc)
abc <- abc %>%
   gather(cycle, frequency, 2:ncol(abc))
abc$cycle <- as.numeric(abc$cycle)
abc <- subset(abc, nt %in% c('A', 'C', 'G', 'T'))
ggplot(abc, aes(x=cycle, y=frequency, color=nt, group=nt)) + geom_line()

  1. Coerce the quality scores to a matrix, and summarize the distribution of qualities across cycle. Is this expected?
